BEGIN_PGML

>> #### Sum and Difference Formulas #### <<

At this point, you should know how to find the trig values of common angles like [`\dfrac{\pi}{6}`], [`\dfrac{\pi}{4}`], [`\dfrac{\pi}{3}`], and  quadrantal angles like [`0`], [`\dfrac{\pi}{2}`], [`\pi`], [`\dfrac{3\pi}{2}`]... *without* using a calculator. The goal now is to combine these trig values to find new trig values by using the *sum and difference formulas*:

>>[` \begin{aligned}
\color{blue}{\sin(\alpha+\beta)} &\quad \color{red}{=}  & \color{blue}{\sin(\alpha)\cos(\beta)+\cos(\alpha)\sin(\beta)} \\
\color{darkgreen}{\sin(\alpha-\beta)} &\quad \color{darkgreen}{=}  & \color{darkgreen}{\sin(\alpha)\cos(\beta)-\cos(\alpha)\sin(\beta)} \\
\color{red}{\cos(\alpha+\beta)} &\quad \color{red}{=}  & \color{red}{\cos(\alpha)\cos(\beta)-\sin(\alpha)\sin(\beta)}\\
\color{orange}{\cos(\alpha-\beta)} &\quad \color{orange}{=}  & \color{orange}{\cos(\alpha)\cos(\beta)+\sin(\alpha)\sin(\beta)}\\
\color{navy}{\tan(\alpha+\beta)} &\quad \color{navy}{=}  & \color{navy}{\dfrac{\tan(\alpha)+\tan(\beta)}{1-\tan(\alpha)\tan(\beta)}}\\
\end{aligned} `]<<

For example, let's consider the angles [`\alpha=\pi`] and [`\beta=\dfrac{\pi}{6}`] and find their sum and difference:

>>[`\color{brown}{\alpha+\beta= \pi  +\dfrac{\pi}{6} = \dfrac{7\pi}{6}}`], <<

>>[`\color{magenta}{\alpha-\beta= \pi  -\dfrac{\pi}{6} = \dfrac{5\pi}{6}}`]. <<

We can find the trig values of [`\color{brown}{\dfrac{7\pi}{6}}`] and
[`\color{magenta}{\dfrac{5\pi}{6}}`] by using the trig values of [`\pi`] and [`\dfrac{\pi}{6}`] into the *sum and difference formulas*:

>>[` \begin{aligned}
\underbrace{\cos\left(\color{brown}{\dfrac{7\pi}{6}}\right)}_{\color{red}{\cos(\alpha+\beta)}}  &= \underbrace{\cos\left(\color{brown}{\pi+\dfrac{\pi}{6}}\right)}_{\color{red}{\cos(\alpha+\beta)}}  =  \underbrace{\cos(\pi)\cos\left(\dfrac{\pi}{6}\right)}_{\color{red}{\cos(\alpha)\cos(\beta)}}\underbrace{-\sin(\pi)\sin\left(\dfrac{\pi}{6}\right)}_{\color{red}{-\quad\sin(\alpha)\sin(\beta)}}
 =   (-1)\cdot \dfrac{\sqrt 3}{2} - 0\cdot \dfrac{1}{2} =  -\dfrac{\sqrt 3}{2} \\
\underbrace{\sin\left(\color{brown}{\dfrac{7\pi}{6}}\right)}_{\color{blue}{\sin(\alpha+\beta)}} &= \underbrace{\sin\left(\color{brown}{\pi+\dfrac{\pi}{6}}\right)}_{\color{blue}{\sin(\alpha+\beta)}} =   \underbrace{\sin(\pi)\cos\left(\dfrac{\pi}{6}\right)}_{\color{blue}{\sin(\alpha)\cos(\beta)}}\underbrace{+\cos(\pi)\sin\left(\dfrac{\pi}{6}\right)}_{\color{blue}{+\quad\cos(\alpha)\sin(\beta)}} = 0\cdot \dfrac{\sqrt 3}{2} +  (-1)\cdot\dfrac{1}{2} =  -\dfrac{1}{2} \\
\underbrace{\cos\left(\color{magenta}{\dfrac{5\pi}{6}}\right)}_{\color{orange}{\cos(\alpha-\beta)}} &= \underbrace{\cos\left(\color{magenta}{\pi-\dfrac{\pi}{6}}\right)}_{\color{orange}{\cos(\alpha-\beta)}} = \underbrace{\cos(\pi)\cos\left(\dfrac{\pi}{6}\right)}_{\color{orange}{\cos(\alpha)\cos(\beta)}}\underbrace{+\sin(\pi)\sin\left(\dfrac{\pi}{6}\right)}_{\color{orange}{+\quad\sin(\alpha)\sin(\beta)}}= (-1)\cdot \dfrac{\sqrt 3}{2} + 0\cdot \dfrac{1}{2} =  -\dfrac{\sqrt 3}{2} \\
\underbrace{\sin\left(\color{magenta}{\dfrac{5\pi}{6}}\right)}_{\color{darkgreen}{\sin(\alpha-\beta)}} &= \underbrace{\sin\left(\color{magenta}{\pi-\dfrac{\pi}{6}}\right)}_{\color{darkgreen}{\sin(\alpha-\beta)}} = \underbrace{\sin(\pi)\cos\left(\dfrac{\pi}{6}\right)}_{\color{darkgreen}{\sin(\alpha)\cos(\beta)}}\underbrace{-\cos(\pi)\sin\left(\dfrac{\pi}{6}\right)}_{\color{darkgreen}{-\quad\cos(\alpha)\sin(\beta)}}= 0\cdot \dfrac{\sqrt 3}{2} -(-1)\cdot \dfrac{1}{2} =  \dfrac{1}{2} 
\end{aligned} `]<<

If we know the cosine and sine values of an angle, then we can find the tangent value using that [`\tan(\theta)=\dfrac{\cos(\theta)}{\sin(\theta)}`].

>>[` \begin{aligned}
\tan\left(\color{brown}{\dfrac{7\pi}{6}}\right)&=\dfrac{\sin\left(\color{brown}{\dfrac{7\pi}{6}}\right)}{\cos\left(\color{brown}{\dfrac{7\pi}{6}}\right)} =\dfrac{-\dfrac{1}{2}}{-\dfrac{\sqrt 3}{2}}=\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{3}} = \dfrac{\sqrt 3}{3} \\
\tan\left(\color{magenta}{\dfrac{5\pi}{6}}\right)&=\dfrac{\sin\left(\color{magenta}{\dfrac{5\pi}{6}}\right)}{\cos\left(\color{magenta}{\dfrac{5\pi}{6}}\right)} =\dfrac{\dfrac{1}{2}}{-\dfrac{\sqrt 3}{2}}=-\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{3}} = -\dfrac{\sqrt 3}{3}
\end{aligned} `]<<

We just saw that if we know

    >>[`\cos(\alpha), \quad\sin(\alpha), \quad\cos(\beta), \quad\sin(\beta)`], <<

then we can find

>> [`\cos(\alpha+\beta),\quad \sin(\alpha+\beta), \quad\tan(\alpha+\beta),\quad\cos(\alpha-\beta),\quad\sin(\alpha-\beta),\quad\tan(\alpha-\beta)`]<<

using the *sum and difference formulas*. So it's important to choose [`\alpha`] and [`\beta`] for which 

>>[`\cos(\alpha), \quad\sin(\alpha), \quad\cos(\beta), \quad\sin(\beta)`] <<

are known or can be calculated. Now suppose that you are asked to find [`[$LHS]`]. We want to view [`[$LHS]`] as

>>  [`\quad [$trig[$function]](\alpha+\beta)\quad`] or [`\quad [$trig[$function]](\alpha-\beta)`].<<

Can you find two angles [`\alpha`] and [`\beta`] such that 
[`\displaystyle[$theta]`] is 

>>[`\alpha+\beta \quad`] or [`\quad \alpha-\beta`],<<

and in addition [`\sin(\alpha)`], [`\cos(\alpha)`], [`\sin(\beta)`], [`\cos(\beta)`] are known or can be calculated?
If so, proceed as above to find [`[$LHS]`].


